x4freetext: For the range of lab angles 60-160 degrees, an
evacuated four-counter array of NaI(T1) detectors,
thermoelectrically cooled, was used to observe protons.
To observe the heavy particle reaction
products, deuterons, tritons, and alpha particles, a
counter telescope mounted in an opening in the wall of
the gas cell which consisted of a 100 mu-m deltaE
surface barrier detector and a 5 mm Si(Li) E detector,
A pair of scintillator detectors located at
+-25 degrees lab were used to examine the centering of
the beam in the gas cell by determining the ratio of
the number of elastically scattered protons observed
in the two counters. A deviation from a pre determined
ratio indicated a shift in location of the centroid of
the beam and the appropriate beam transport parameters
The oxygen gas used as a target was contained in a
cell which isolated the gas by means of a 50 mu-pm
thick Kapton H foil which covered a 5.1 cm high gap
that extended 330 degrees around the cell. The target
gas was natural oxygen of 99.99 % purity. The gas
pressure was measured with a precision dial manometer
which had an accuracy of 0.1% of full scale.
No corrections were made to the data for effects due
to finite counter geometry, change in beam profile
across the target gas, or reactions occurring in the
detectors. The magnitude of all these effects was
usually about 1.5 %. All of these corrections vary
slowly with energy and were not expected to seriously
modify the excitation functions. They constitute an
additional error in the absolute magnitude of the
For the most of these data the relative errors are
smaller than the size of the points.
Contributions to the uncertainty in the absolute scale
of the measurements:  ERR-1 through ERR-10.

The relative errors refer to errors between
measurements at different angles for a fixed energy.
